{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782856488,"nonce":"IrsCKrdydMMKqO2u+1fO+E3ti5w=","title":"SQLite view rendering (needs Dialect seams for schema suppression + scalar-function names)","message":"The SQLite backend (a92e39f) currently defers view rendering: `Sqlite::render_create` returns an `Unsupported` error if the model carries any views (PR #68). The blocker is the shared view-body renderer (squealy::render_create_view / view_render.rs), which emits PostgreSQL/MySQL spellings SQLite rejects:\n\n- **Schema-qualified sources**: a view over `app.users` renders `FROM \"app\".\"users\"`, but SQLite has no schemas and tables are unqualified (`\"app\"` would be read as an attached database). Need a Dialect seam to suppress schema qualification in source refs.\n- **Scalar-function names**: `ScalarFunc::Length` renders `CHAR_LENGTH(...)`; SQLite's builtin is `length(...)`. Need a backend-specific scalar-function-name seam (also needed by the query layer in the next SQLite PR for `squealy::length(...)` in query bodies). Audit the other ScalarFunc spellings for SQLite too.\n\n## Scope\n- Add the Dialect seam(s): e.g. `qualify_source_schema() -\u003e bool` (default true; SQLite false) honored by view_render.rs / render.rs, and a scalar-function-name hook (or per-fn override) so each backend spells builtins its own way.\n- Then render SQLite views in `render_create` (drop the deferral error) and add cross-backend view render tests.\n\nPart of the SQLite backend epic (a92e39f). Lands alongside or after the SQLite query layer, which needs the scalar-function seam regardless.","files":null}]}